    <h2>Breakfast Smoothie Meal Prep Guide</h2>

    <h3>The Sunday Prep Method (15 Minutes)</h3>
    <p><strong>Step 1:</strong> Get 5-7 freezer bags (one per weekday)</p>
    <p><strong>Step 2:</strong> Portion out dry/frozen ingredients per bag:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>1 frozen banana (pre-peeled)</li>
      <li>Any other frozen fruit</li>
      <li>Greens (spinach, kale)</li>
      <li>Seeds (chia, flax, hemp)</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Step 3:</strong> Label bags (Monday-Friday) and freeze</p>
    <p><strong>Step 4:</strong> Each morning, dump bag + add liquid + protein powder + blend</p>

    <p><strong>Result:</strong> 2-minute breakfast smoothies all week!</p>

    <h2>Common Breakfast Smoothie Mistakes</h2>

    <h3>❌ Mistake #1: Not Enough Protein</h3>
    <p>Smoothies with just fruit leave you hungry in 1 hour. Always add protein powder or Greek yogurt. 
    Aim for 20-30g protein per smoothie.</p>

    <h3>❌ Mistake #2: Too Much Fruit</h3>
    <p>3 bananas + berries + mango = sugar bomb. Stick to 1-1.5 servings of fruit max. Add greens for volume.</p>

    <h3>❌ Mistake #3: Making It the Night Before</h3>
    <p>Pre-blended smoothies separate and get gross overnight. Prep ingredients in bags, but blend fresh each morning.</p>

    <h3>❌ Mistake #4: Using Juice as Base</h3>
    <p>Orange juice = liquid sugar. Use almond milk, oat milk, or regular milk instead. Adds creaminess without sugar spike.</p>

    <h3>❌ Mistake #5: Skipping Healthy Fats</h3>
    <p>Fat = satiety. Add nut butter, avocado, or seeds. You'll stay full way longer.</p>

    <h2>FAQ: Breakfast Smoothies</h2>

    <h3>Q: Can I have smoothies for breakfast every day?</h3>
    <p><strong>A:</strong> Yes! As long as they're balanced (protein + carbs + fat + fiber). Many people do this for months/years with great results.</p>

    <h3>Q: Will I be hungry before lunch?</h3>
    <p><strong>A:</strong> Not if you follow the formula (20-30g protein, healthy fats, fiber). These smoothies keep you full 4-5 hours.</p>

    <h3>Q: Are breakfast smoothies good for weight loss?</h3>
    <p><strong>A:</strong> Yes! They're portion-controlled (vs endless cereal bowls) and high in protein/fiber. Most people naturally eat less when they start with smoothies.</p>

    <h3>Q: What if I don't have time in the morning?</h3>
    <p><strong>A:</strong> Use the freezer bag meal prep method. Dump bag in blender, add liquid + protein, blend. 2 minutes flat.</p>

    <h3>Q: Do I need an expensive blender?</h3>
    <p><strong>A:</strong> Not for these recipes. A $50-100 Ninja or Nutribullet works great. Vitamix is nice but overkill for simple smoothies.</p>

